WEBVTT

00:00.034 --> 00:03.697
The following message by Alistair Begg is made available by Truth For Life.

00:04.498 --> 00:08.462
For more information visit us online at truthforlife.org.

00:09.903 --> 00:16.209
I invite you to take your Bible and turn with me to the Gospel of Mark and to chapter 14.

00:18.371 --> 00:29.842
Mark, chapter 14, it was now two days before the Passover and the Feast of Unleavened Bread, and the chief priests and the scribes were seeking how to arrest him by stealth and kill him.

00:30.370 --> 00:34.938
for they said, not during the feast, lest there be an uproar from the people.

00:35.959 --> 00:50.083
And while he was at Bethany in the house of Simon the leper, as he was reclining at table, a woman came with an alabaster flask of ointment of pure nard very costly, and she broke the flask and poured it over his head.

00:51.085 --> 00:56.594
There were some who said to themselves indignantly, why was the ointment wasted like that?

00:57.186 --> 01:03.835
For this ointment could have been sold for more than 300 denariant given to the poor, and they scolded her.

01:04.776 --> 01:06.478
But Jesus said, leave her alone.

01:06.519 --> 01:07.600
Why do you trouble her?

01:07.620 --> 01:09.462
She's done a beautiful thing to me.

01:10.444 --> 01:15.210
For you always have the poor with you, and whenever you want, you can do good for them.

01:15.250 --> 01:17.513
But you will not always have me.

01:17.573 --> 01:20.858
She has done what she could.

01:21.939 --> 01:27.026
She has anointed my body beforehand for burial, and truly I say to you,

01:27.394 --> 01:34.764
wherever the gospel is proclaimed in the whole world, what she has done will be told in memory of her.

01:36.546 --> 01:36.907
Amen.

01:38.569 --> 01:50.605
Now we're going to give attention to this attractive picture which is here for us recorded by Mark set in the context of the unattractive plot which is the surrounding story.

01:51.827 --> 01:54.290
The beauty and loyalty of this woman

01:54.690 --> 01:58.917
is said against the animosity of the religious leaders.

02:00.099 --> 02:14.162
And Mark has been telling his readers for some time that these religious authorities were about the business of seeking some sly way as the NIV puts it, some sly way to arrest Jesus.

02:14.923 --> 02:19.090
They were seeking quite straightforwardly a way to destroy him.

02:19.714 --> 02:27.705
Jesus was no longer, John tells us, able to walk openly and freely among the Jewish people because there was essentially a price on his head.

02:28.466 --> 02:33.012
They had given word that if anybody knew of his whereabouts, they should come and report it.

02:33.753 --> 02:40.722
Little did they realize that the one who would respond to their invitation would be one of the core group, even Judas himself.

02:41.666 --> 03:09.586
And Mark is actually inviting his readers to see, if you like, the unfolding of that which is described in the second Sam where we read of the leaders taking their plotting in vain against the lords anointed and seeking to do in a secretive way what God is now about to overturn as he sets his holy king on the holy hill of Zion.

03:10.338 --> 03:17.067
And what I'd like to do is simply take three phrases out of this passage in order to help us navigate our way.

03:17.888 --> 03:26.520
In light of our time, I won't be as fulsome as perhaps I would otherwise have been, but nevertheless, enough I think at least to get us started.

03:27.120 --> 03:34.290
I made one or two homiletical comments as I'm going along because I recognize that many of us are here as preachers.

03:34.530 --> 03:44.685
In fact, let me make a homolytical comment immediately, and that is, when you come to verse three of this passage, you need to make a decision about whether you're going to spend two or three minutes talking about Simon and leper.

03:45.306 --> 03:50.473
I suggest you don't, and so I'm not going to spend two or three minutes telling you why I don't think you should.

03:50.874 --> 03:55.440
You can just go, and you can just go and figure that out for yourselves.

03:55.561 --> 03:57.403
Here are the three phrases.

03:58.184 --> 04:02.130
A woman came, that's in verse three, which gives to us

04:02.306 --> 04:04.770
an opportunity to consider her action.

04:05.511 --> 04:21.575
They scolded her, and you will find that down there somewhere in the passage, which gives us an opportunity to consider their reaction, and then Jesus commended her, which you'll find later on down in the text as well.

04:22.076 --> 04:23.178
I can't do everything for you.

04:23.218 --> 04:24.299
Find these things for yourself.

04:24.600 --> 04:26.162
That's why you have a Bible.

04:29.730 --> 04:33.395
You're not going to find me putting my cheat sheet up on the wall for you.

04:33.415 --> 04:34.877
Do some work yourselves.

04:34.957 --> 04:37.701
First of all, a woman came.

04:37.721 --> 04:39.363
A woman came.

04:40.284 --> 04:45.291
It's just a very striking way in which the text unfolds that our woman came.

04:47.474 --> 04:56.146
We've just come out of the Olivet Discourse, the great apocalyptic passage, and preceding that, notably, is the story of another woman.

04:56.642 --> 04:58.544
The story of another woman's generosity.

04:58.564 --> 05:00.786
That's how Mark chapter 12 ends.

05:01.587 --> 05:05.210
Jesus has been teaching his disciples the values of the kingdom.

05:05.230 --> 05:06.772
They've not been getting it very well.

05:07.512 --> 05:23.307
And as he sits opposite the treasury, Mark tells us, he notices this particular individual, you know her, and she had put this very, very small amount of money into one of these trumpets, barely making a noise.

05:24.128 --> 05:26.290
And yet Jesus introduces her

05:26.434 --> 05:32.143
to his disciples and he says, you know, this lady has actually put in more than all the rest.

05:32.684 --> 05:40.736
He actually introduces her by saying, or the comment, truly I say to you, or in the King James Version, verily I say to you.

05:40.756 --> 05:43.401
In other words, fellows, why want you to get a hold of this?

05:43.901 --> 05:46.926
She has done this, put in more than all the rest.

05:47.868 --> 05:54.578
And of course they don't get that at all because Jesus is talking about it being measured by sacrifice and not by amount.

05:55.042 --> 06:01.490
He's talking about it being measured by proportion, because two cents out of two cents is a factor of one.

06:01.510 --> 06:05.134
A thousand out of ten thousand is a factor of a tenth.

06:06.956 --> 06:16.427
And there she stands or walks away as an illustration of what it means to be devoted to the Lord Jesus Christ.

06:17.348 --> 06:22.194
The disciples now having diverted the challenge of that, I think,

06:22.274 --> 06:27.005
I may be reading into it, but it is interesting is that what happens at the end of a sermon?

06:27.626 --> 06:31.054
But people come up and say, I noticed that you were wearing a striped tie this morning placer.

06:31.074 --> 06:32.017
It was quite remarkable.

06:32.738 --> 06:37.750
And you say, did you have any consideration of the message at all?

06:37.770 --> 06:41.298
Or do you just want to talk about dress codes or whatever it is?

06:41.538 --> 06:46.183
As Virgin talks about that, and I'm so glad that he does, because I thought it only happened to me.

06:46.223 --> 06:48.826
But if it happened to him, I'd feel so much better about it.

06:49.387 --> 06:52.770
You preach your heart out, and then they ask you some trivial nonsense.

06:53.351 --> 07:00.138
Well, Jesus gives them an amazing illustration, and they immediately start to talk about the architecture.

07:00.659 --> 07:03.702
Chapter 13 opens straight up, do you see this woman?

07:03.722 --> 07:05.184
She's put in more than all the rest.

07:05.464 --> 07:08.287
One of them says, you know, these buildings are really fantastic.

07:09.188 --> 07:10.770
I can't.

07:16.354 --> 07:24.766
He says, well, let me tell you about the buildings, then we have the apocalyptic discourse, then the plot darkens, the plot thickens, and the scribes are more and more on their way.

07:25.086 --> 07:37.083
The shadow is coming over the soul of Judas himself, and into the midst of all of this darkness is beautiful light shines in the house of this man and in the appearing of this lady.

07:37.764 --> 07:44.914
Now, you will notice that Mark tells us about the container, and about the content, and about the cost.

07:45.698 --> 07:56.550
In other words, he's making it clear for his readers that this material is not something that the lady would have picked up at Nordstrom on the way for an evening at dinner.

07:57.231 --> 08:00.295
It's not something that she would have carried routinely in her purse.

08:01.276 --> 08:06.502
No, it was the cost of her action that was the occasion of the disapproval.

08:07.583 --> 08:13.810
This perfume or this ointment cost a year's wages.

08:14.786 --> 08:16.108
Now that's all we really need to know.

08:17.310 --> 08:19.633
Those of you who, and this is another homiletical comment.

08:20.394 --> 08:30.910
When you come to the phrase of pure nard, I suggest to you that it is of little value to you to spend a long time letting everybody know how little you know about pure nard.

08:32.212 --> 08:32.472
Right?

08:32.973 --> 08:44.370
How little you know about Indian vegetation, how little you know about Himalayan plant life, because your congregation knows that you can't tell the difference between a daffodil and a chul.

08:44.898 --> 08:50.707
So it is a major distraction for you simply to launch off on pure nard.

08:51.228 --> 08:56.556
And you may be sure that they are sitting there saying, he is a pure nerd trying to talk about pure nard.

08:58.639 --> 08:58.959
All right?

09:00.782 --> 09:02.304
So on that basis, let me move on.

09:04.247 --> 09:10.777
John tells us that the pungency of this material was such that the fragrance filled the entire house.

09:10.797 --> 09:14.002
But the monetary value of it was really not the cost.

09:14.850 --> 09:21.979
If we understand this correctly, this kind of material would be in the home of a lady like this, probably for one of two reasons.

09:22.920 --> 09:37.298
Either that it would be used as a dowry on the occasion of her wedding, or that it would be used in the manner in which she is about to use it, but instead of being used on a third party, actually used upon herself.

09:37.698 --> 09:52.255
In other words, retained in order that in the prospect of her own burial, she may be the beneficiary of the large s of that which is contained in this alabaster flask or alabaster jar.

09:53.416 --> 10:00.284
If you think about it in those terms, then you realize that the action of the lady was a pouring out of her future, if you like.

10:00.965 --> 10:05.330
She was pouring out her future on the head of the Lord Jesus Christ.

10:05.762 --> 10:13.410
She was, in a very real sense, surrendering her own plans, her own ambitions, her own aspirations.

10:14.551 --> 10:25.943
In one sense, her security, that which represented a year's wages, would have potential value if things were to go wrong.

10:26.924 --> 10:33.010
But instead, she chooses to pour this out on the head of the Lord Jesus Christ.

10:33.538 --> 10:35.421
She breaks the flask, we're told.

10:35.441 --> 10:39.147
She broke the flask and poured it over his head.

10:40.088 --> 10:42.933
Was this a gesture of complete abandonment?

10:43.915 --> 10:49.003
Once broken, the flask, having served its purpose, could be discarded.

10:50.265 --> 10:53.650
We're not told that she coaxed the top off.

10:53.986 --> 11:04.619
and eked out a little on Christ as a gesture, quickly putting the top back on and retaining all the rest of it for the purposes that she already had in mind.

11:05.481 --> 11:19.739
Whatever was in her mind, in the occasion confronted by the opportunity, the flask is broken, the fragrance is spread, and Christ is deluged by this extravagant gesture on the part of this lady.

11:20.660 --> 11:22.482
If it was

11:22.882 --> 11:31.270
A moment of extravagance, it was a moment of extravagance that clearly was grounded in a time of premeditation.

11:31.911 --> 11:37.656
Because as we've already noted, this was not the kind of thing that she would simply be carrying with her.

11:38.177 --> 11:51.890
Therefore, somewhere in the quietness of her own life, somewhere in the privacy of her own heart, somewhere in the secrecy of her own home, she determined that on this occasion she would do this for Christ.

11:52.258 --> 11:58.567
She proceeded to the moment in order to do as she had done.

11:58.607 --> 12:10.924
Now, here again, homologically, is an aside that I wouldn't necessarily want to dwell on, but it is worth saying to oneself, I think, and how would Christ have received this?

12:12.246 --> 12:20.498
We understand the routine gesture of hospitality in an Eastern context in terms of foot washing and anointing and so on.

12:21.602 --> 12:33.340
But I wondered whether Jesus would not have experienced this and found himself saying inside of himself, you prepare a table before me in the presence of my enemies.

12:34.642 --> 12:36.304
You anoint my head with oil.

12:36.344 --> 12:38.788
Father, my cup runs over.

12:38.828 --> 12:44.276
Surely goodness and mercy will follow me all the days of my life.

12:47.141 --> 12:50.706
And the darkness of the night settles in.

12:52.034 --> 12:56.742
And the anticipation of his crucifixion is before him.

12:58.284 --> 13:08.401
And in the midst of that, this expression of devotion on the part of a lady who is anonymous in Mark's record.

13:10.043 --> 13:19.218
We must leave our action there, aware of the fact that it is unique in its thoughtfulness, it is general, generous in its bestowal

13:19.810 --> 13:23.695
and it is timely as we're about to see in its provision.

13:25.937 --> 13:26.858
So a woman came.

13:27.159 --> 13:35.669
Secondly, you will notice, and there were some who said to themselves indignantly, why was this ointment used in this way?

13:35.709 --> 13:39.493
And at the end of verse 5, they scolded her.

13:39.934 --> 13:40.755
They scolded her.

13:42.396 --> 13:44.119
Reactions are an interesting thing, isn't it?

13:44.339 --> 13:47.122
Especially when somebody does something as striking as this.

13:47.746 --> 13:49.088
We ought to be surprised by this.

13:49.148 --> 13:54.173
The trouble with so many of us is that we know our Bibles do well, or we know these records too well.

13:54.654 --> 13:57.517
I wish sometimes I could read the Bible for the first time all over again.

13:58.118 --> 14:12.434
And my anticipation presumably would be that when the lady had finished this, if they were operating on kind of early 20th century sort of response, then it would have said, and they bowed humbly in the awareness of what had taken place.

14:12.994 --> 14:20.665
If they were operating on the basis of late 20th century, early 21st century response, then it would have said, and they all burst into applause.

14:21.786 --> 14:25.912
And they said, how, what a wonderful thing to do, and how exciting this is.

14:26.553 --> 14:28.716
What you're not prepared for is what it says.

14:30.178 --> 14:35.465
A lady comes in and does this for Jesus, and they begin to grumble to one another, and they growl at her.

14:36.066 --> 14:38.008
They're indignant about what is taking place.

14:38.469 --> 14:40.512
And as a result, they scold her.

14:40.912 --> 14:42.194
They snort at her.

14:42.818 --> 14:46.022
She now is the object of their disapproval.

14:46.542 --> 14:52.068
In many ways, she has not only sacrificed her future, but she has also sacrificed her present.

14:52.088 --> 15:00.798
She has sacrificed social acceptability in the moment, because what she has done is not met with alacrity, it is met with disapproval.

15:03.080 --> 15:11.890
Angry glances, shocked comments, they regard it her action as extravagant, as wasteful, as a misuse

15:12.002 --> 15:12.903
of resources.

15:14.847 --> 15:22.579
And they thought they could take the high ground and explain their reaction in terms of a concern for the poor.

15:22.619 --> 15:28.589
This ointment could have been sold for more than 300 denari and given to the poor.

15:29.791 --> 15:39.346
But their express concern for the poor is a thin disguise for the fact that they have cold hearts and they have tight fists.

15:40.386 --> 15:47.955
The disciples are once again on the wrong side of the equation when it comes to the values of the kingdom of God.

15:48.696 --> 15:57.747
The disciples, although led by Judas in this, as we're told in the parallel passage, the disciples are themselves opposed to what is taking place.

15:58.408 --> 16:03.794
These are the ones who have heard Jesus say, unless you take up your cross and follow me, you will never be my disciple.

16:04.098 --> 16:07.662
These are the ones who have heard Jesus say, don't first go and deal with your field.

16:07.722 --> 16:09.304
Don't first go and bury your father.

16:09.584 --> 16:10.766
You come and follow me.

16:10.786 --> 16:12.648
They had heard that firsthand.

16:12.688 --> 16:16.612
They knew that that was part of what it meant to be a disciple of Jesus Christ.

16:17.313 --> 16:32.530
And so now in the presence of a lady who makes this extravagant gesture, instead of their response being one of approval, they join Judas in expressing their concerns as being in another direction.

16:34.018 --> 16:39.068
Judas couldn't fathom anybody who would waste something so valuable in such a basis.

16:40.251 --> 16:45.542
Later on he was going to go to the very religious leaders and ask them this question, what will you give me?

16:45.602 --> 16:47.666
What will you give me?

16:48.450 --> 17:00.785
Judas is a classic illustration of a person who ostensibly walks with Christ as close to Christ and yet exactly opposed to Christ at his core, only interested in what he may get from it.

17:01.125 --> 17:07.953
And such an individual will always be opposed to the extravagant gestures of women and men who are prepared to do this.

17:07.973 --> 17:15.442
Jesse Ryle in the 19th century comments, the spirit of these narrow-minded fault-finders is unhappily only too common.

17:16.354 --> 17:21.222
Their followers and successors are to be found in every part of Christ's visible church.

17:21.943 --> 17:35.444
There is never wanting a generation of people who decry what they call extremes in religion and are incessantly recommending what they term moderation in the service of Christ.

17:36.446 --> 17:44.178
If a man devotes his time, money, and affection to the pursuit of worldly things, they do not blame him.

17:44.418 --> 17:48.604
He gives himself up to the service of money, pleasure, or politics.

17:49.084 --> 17:50.146
They find no fault.

17:51.207 --> 17:59.098
But if that man devotes himself and all he has to Christ, they can scarcely find words to express their sense of folly.

17:59.919 --> 18:01.080
He is beside himself.

18:01.701 --> 18:02.783
He is out of his mind.

18:03.424 --> 18:04.805
He is an enthusiast.

18:05.366 --> 18:07.249
He is a fanatic.

18:10.153 --> 18:14.098
The broken flask, the fragrant scent,

18:14.690 --> 18:18.556
testified against their calculated pragmatism.

18:19.938 --> 18:29.794
If this lady had arrived at this house and sought the approval of this group before she did what she did, she would never have done it.

18:30.555 --> 18:34.962
There would be no record of it in the scriptures because we would have talked her out of it.

18:35.426 --> 18:45.700
They would have talked or out of it using high sounding language about why this was an unnecessary thing to do, why this was a wasteful thing to do, why this was an extreme thing to do.

18:46.661 --> 18:54.631
Now my dear friends and brothers and sisters, listen, the real challenge that is contained in this passage is the challenge to face ourselves in it.

18:55.573 --> 19:02.642
We all want to say we're the lady, but I have a sneaking suspicion that many of us are part of the disciple band.

19:03.202 --> 19:04.583
We are the pragmatists.

19:04.884 --> 19:08.647
We are the one who's saying, you can't invest all that for the kingdom of God.

19:08.948 --> 19:11.270
You can't throw your life away for the gospel.

19:11.811 --> 19:31.570
Somebody told me just the other day that their daughter or son had been at a Christian college and the chaplain of the college had been challenged by a father who said to the chaplain, I don't like you moving my child in the direction of world missions.

19:31.810 --> 19:41.804
I did not, said he many years ago, give $80,000 to this institution to have my child throw his or her life away.

19:43.286 --> 19:44.728
That's a Christian university.

19:45.209 --> 19:45.950
Not this one.

19:48.093 --> 19:51.637
No, I tell you, we'd be right there, wouldn't we?

19:52.278 --> 19:54.562
With George Sr. Not gonna do it.

19:57.165 --> 19:58.006
Wouldn't be prudent.

19:59.629 --> 20:00.690
Not of this juncture.

20:05.282 --> 20:12.051
The lady was scolded on account of the fight that her gratitude to Jesus caused her to give up her dearest possession.

20:12.932 --> 20:14.133
That's why they scolded her.

20:20.221 --> 20:25.427
Now her action might be overplayed, but it dare not be underestimated.

20:27.070 --> 20:27.450
C.T.

20:27.490 --> 20:28.411
Stud in his day.

20:29.453 --> 20:32.076
Missionary biography is so helpful in this regard, isn't it?

20:32.096 --> 20:32.556
But C.T.

20:32.597 --> 20:33.778
Stud in his day was

20:33.986 --> 20:39.815
Cambridge University, the high echelons of English society, exceptionally wealthy background.

20:39.875 --> 20:41.257
His father had become a Christian.

20:41.337 --> 20:42.819
He, in turn, became a Christian.

20:42.899 --> 20:44.982
His wife was a Christian.

20:47.105 --> 20:54.516
And God so moved in his heart that he determined he must turn his back on all of this and go bury himself in Africa for the cause of the gospel.

20:54.536 --> 20:57.120
And people said the same things about CT study in his day.

20:57.420 --> 20:58.642
This spell is crazy.

20:58.978 --> 20:59.899
What does he think he's doing?

21:00.279 --> 21:00.640
C.T.

21:00.680 --> 21:12.413
Stud actually had been going somewhere and he heard two lines repeated and the lines were, only one life will soon be passed, only what's done for Jesus will last.

21:12.433 --> 21:22.303
He actually heard somebody say that and he went home to think about it and he wrote a fairly extensive poem which you can find on the internet and it ends with those two lines all the way through.

21:22.343 --> 21:24.786
Turning his back on

21:24.898 --> 21:29.184
all that represented stability, security, and notoriety to him.

21:29.725 --> 21:30.826
He was about to head out.

21:31.747 --> 21:42.161
He had taught his wife that she must understand how important the Lord Jesus was to her, that her security was in the Lord Jesus and not in her husband, Charlie.

21:42.702 --> 21:50.713
And so in the process of schooling her in that direction, he gave her a little poem that she was supposed to say each morning when she was having her quiet time.

21:51.294 --> 21:52.695
And this is what he taught her to say.

21:52.736 --> 21:54.578
Dear Lord Jesus,

21:54.850 --> 21:59.577
You are to me, Dearer than Charlie ever could be."

22:00.339 --> 22:03.303
It's quite good, not quite poetry, but the sentiment is helpful.

22:03.964 --> 22:06.388
One day he would be gone, Jesus the King would remain.

22:06.428 --> 22:08.491
He wanted her to be secure in him.

22:08.531 --> 22:10.234
He was leading her in that way.

22:10.274 --> 22:14.541
The trouble was he didn't do it in its entirety.

22:14.601 --> 22:20.670
She found out that when he gave away his fortune, he held back 100,000 pounds for her.

22:21.171 --> 22:23.154
In today's currency, that is millions.

22:23.458 --> 22:26.241
So in other words, he kept a portfolio just for his wife.

22:26.822 --> 22:28.524
She found out she chided him.

22:28.804 --> 22:29.765
What about the poem?

22:30.206 --> 22:33.530
What about the fight that God can look after me the way he looks after you?

22:33.850 --> 22:37.214
So she said, Charlie, give my 100,000 away as well.

22:37.535 --> 22:45.704
He said where or to whom she said to William Booth, the founder of the Salvation Army, and they gave their money away there.

22:46.926 --> 22:48.407
Now what was the context?

22:48.628 --> 22:50.770
It's the same value system.

22:52.610 --> 22:53.351
This is stud.

22:54.313 --> 23:04.450
If Jesus Christ be God and died for me, then no sacrifice that I could ever make for Him could ever be too great."

23:05.932 --> 23:08.657
Our contemporary culture has no problem with philanthropy.

23:09.739 --> 23:13.745
Gates and Buffett are heroes for dibbling around and dabbling around in their billions.

23:13.765 --> 23:14.907
Who's to gain say that?

23:15.268 --> 23:18.994
I'm very glad that the money would be used for something profitable I trust.

23:19.490 --> 23:24.997
The Cleveland Clinic is full of people's names who are now testifying to the world how amazingly generous they are.

23:25.357 --> 23:27.160
And nobody has any real concern about that.

23:27.280 --> 23:32.046
Millions and millions and billions have been spent in this political exercise.

23:32.366 --> 23:37.633
And people are heroes and they have large plates of food and give large plates of money.

23:37.653 --> 23:41.938
And everybody says this is terrific stuff.

23:41.958 --> 23:45.202
But just don't go crazy on this Jesus thing.

23:46.402 --> 23:50.246
Just don't go crazy on the exclusive claims of Jesus of Nazareth.

23:51.107 --> 24:00.137
Just don't go crazy on believing in the sufficiency, an authority of the word that is proclaimed because actually that is not as palatable.

24:01.238 --> 24:11.770
Smitten in his book on the atonement says to convert one sinner from the error of his way is an event of greater importance than the deliverance of a whole kingdom from temporal evil.

24:13.832 --> 24:15.634
Putting again these questions.

24:15.842 --> 24:16.683
in perspective.

24:16.923 --> 24:20.728
Well, our time is almost gone, so we'll go to our third heading, right?

24:21.488 --> 24:33.802
A woman came, she was devoted, and they reacted, they scolded her, so she's devoted, she scolded, and finally she is commended, verse 8.

24:34.463 --> 24:37.907
Jesus says, well, verse 7, you'll always have the poor with you.

24:37.927 --> 24:39.869
He says, this is an ongoing obligation.

24:40.951 --> 24:43.954
This is something that is your opportunity for all time.

24:45.826 --> 24:48.509
But in actual fact, you won't have me forever.

24:48.570 --> 24:53.976
As we say in the United Kingdom, Jesus would have said to them, you know, what this lady has done is a one-off.

24:54.657 --> 24:57.741
There's not going to be another opportunity for this kind of thing to happen.

24:58.702 --> 25:02.127
They scolded her and Jesus reprimanded them.

25:03.388 --> 25:04.129
Leave her alone.

25:05.231 --> 25:07.173
Why do you trouble her?

25:08.054 --> 25:10.898
She's done a beautiful thing for me.

25:12.610 --> 25:13.992
And then he's actually quoting the law.

25:14.052 --> 25:15.594
He's actually quoting Exodus 21.

25:15.614 --> 25:17.937
There will never cease to be the poor in the land.

25:18.919 --> 25:20.120
Don't let's go wrong on this.

25:20.240 --> 25:22.584
Jesus understand perfectly what Jesus is saying.

25:22.884 --> 25:27.110
The ongoing opportunity and obligation for dealing with the poor is just that.

25:27.851 --> 25:31.376
But this experience, this moment in time, is unique.

25:32.537 --> 25:35.842
And what this lady has done is so striking.

25:36.122 --> 25:41.970
She's done a beautiful thing, callous, not just agathos, not just intrinsically good, but beautifully good.

25:42.434 --> 25:44.397
She has done what she could.

25:44.457 --> 25:46.419
What has she done?

25:46.479 --> 25:48.182
Well, he says, let me tell you what she's actually done.

25:48.222 --> 25:50.865
She's anointed my body beforehand for burial.

25:52.287 --> 25:57.554
Now, the commentators largely say that this lady has done this unwittingly.

25:58.135 --> 25:59.517
I personally am not convinced.

25:59.617 --> 26:01.079
I don't think we have to say that.

26:02.301 --> 26:09.170
They say that she has done this in the way that Caiaphas said something greater than what he knew he was actually saying.

26:10.178 --> 26:15.304
This explanation by Jesus gives a greater theological context to what is going on.

26:16.605 --> 26:19.028
This possible other lady knew exactly what she was doing.

26:20.209 --> 26:22.212
There is something about female intuition.

26:23.213 --> 26:29.980
There is something about the gift of God in opening the eyes that are dimmed to reality.

26:31.262 --> 26:38.610
I wouldn't be at all surprised if these fat-headed disciples didn't need a little

26:38.690 --> 26:43.977
lesson from an anonymous lady about what was actually going on here.

26:44.057 --> 26:52.027
After all, God opened the eyes of the thief on the cross to say, we are up here getting what we deserve, but this man has done nothing wrong.

26:52.328 --> 26:53.790
How in the world did that happen?

26:55.291 --> 26:58.335
Well, in the same way that something like this would happen, the lady came.

27:00.178 --> 27:03.442
The demands of the law were for an anointing before burial.

27:04.162 --> 27:21.603
The way in which Jesus was about to be arrested and beaten and finally crucified gave no opportunity for those demands of Allah to be met and hear this lady, wittingly or unwittingly, is doing that, which was a necessary prerequisite for the death of the Lord Jesus himself.

27:21.663 --> 27:29.993
How immense, how amazing, how mysterious are the ways of God, intersecting from eternity with the issues of a moment in time.

27:30.053 --> 27:34.098
It is a wonderful, wonderful thing.

27:35.042 --> 27:41.970
Truly I say to you, truly I say to you what she has done, what she has done.

27:42.010 --> 27:51.902
Now the disciples, I just want to say a final thing about the disciples because they really are, they really are a bad bunch aren't they?

27:51.922 --> 27:58.911
That's why I want to suggest, don't jump too quickly, don't go out of here and say, I'm the lady, you're not.

28:00.973 --> 28:04.818
Let's be honest, you're one of the disciples, they were upside down

28:05.474 --> 28:14.669
right through the resurrection, right onto the Emmaus Road, and desperately in need in the fulfillment of the promise of the giving of the Holy Spirit, who would lead them into all the truth, right?

28:15.350 --> 28:17.233
I mean, just take a smattering of it.

28:18.735 --> 28:26.287
Lord Jesus, we were out this afternoon, and we saw a man casting out demons in your name, and we told them to stop.

28:30.634 --> 28:33.298
Jesus says, don't tell him to stop.

28:33.602 --> 28:38.647
One of the disciples says, see, I told you not to tell him to stop.

28:38.667 --> 28:39.368
It was stupid.

28:39.988 --> 28:40.309
I knew.

28:43.032 --> 28:45.554
Could you move the children back, please?

28:45.834 --> 28:48.337
Jesus is doing evangelism and healings.

28:48.397 --> 28:49.018
We can get them.

28:49.538 --> 28:51.860
No, no, just pardon?

28:51.880 --> 28:52.161
Oh, yeah.

28:52.181 --> 28:55.524
As I was saying, bring them a little, yes.

28:56.946 --> 28:57.546
No, no.

28:58.087 --> 29:01.330
Right up, on his knees, on his knees.

29:05.442 --> 29:08.346
Just back from the Samaritan villages, Jesus, not good.

29:08.926 --> 29:10.108
Wasn't a good response.

29:11.470 --> 29:14.253
Would you like us to call down fire from heaven and burn them?

29:17.017 --> 29:18.619
Jesus says, no, not this afternoon.

29:18.659 --> 29:19.339
No, I don't think.

29:19.380 --> 29:22.784
I don't think so.

29:22.804 --> 29:23.725
And here we are again.

29:24.926 --> 29:34.098
Lady comes in, takes her future, sacrifices on the head of Jesus, anoints him for his burial, and these fellows

29:34.210 --> 29:35.332
Just don't get it.

29:36.775 --> 29:39.581
Such extravagant wastefulness for the kingdom of God.

29:39.942 --> 29:42.206
And we are the core group.

29:42.226 --> 29:46.234
We are the boys who know how little did they know.

29:47.437 --> 29:55.954
The self-contained sensible scolding of these onlookers fades into obscurity.

29:57.250 --> 30:05.201
While the lasting value of the action, the extravagant action of a humble woman is to be known wherever the gospel is preached.

30:06.422 --> 30:27.250
Long after human eloquence and human brilliance are forgotten, when the deeds and the tales of emperors and kings and presidents are buried in the dust, Jesus says, this beautiful, significant, and timely act will be remembered.

30:28.770 --> 30:34.357
because the pathway to lasting honor is to honor Christ.

30:36.539 --> 30:37.240
Leave her alone.

30:38.582 --> 30:39.944
She has done what she could.

30:42.126 --> 30:58.546
What she did was unique in its thoughtfulness, costly in its bestowal, timely in its provision, challenging in its impact and lasting in its manner.

31:00.258 --> 31:17.479
Only the power of the cross established in our stubborn, selfish hearts might bring us to this similar place of wholehearted devotion to Jesus.

31:19.561 --> 31:30.194
So, Grant, then, Father, that what we know not, you will teach us what we have not, you will give us, what we are not,

31:31.138 --> 31:34.983
You will make us, for we pray in Christ's name.

31:35.965 --> 31:36.305
Amen.

